Nginx Multi-Domain Setup Guide

Prerequisites
A Linux server (Debian/Ubuntu distribution assumed).
sudo or root privileges.
DNS A-records for both domains pointing to the server's public IP address.

tep 1: Update Packages & Install Nginx

Ensure your package lists are up-to-date before installing the web server.

Before you start, you must have a domain name (like example.com) pointed to your server's IP address (160.x.x.x).

Go to your domain registrar (Namecheap, GoDaddy, etc.).
Add an A Record with Name @ pointing to 160.x.x.x.
Add a A Record Record with Name www pointing to @.

Step 1: Install Nginx and Firewall
bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt install nginx -y
sudo ufw allow 'Nginx Full'

Step 2: Install MySQL (Database)
You'll need this to store data for most modern websites.
sudo apt install mysql-server -y
sudo mysql_secure_installation
Pro-Tip: When it asks for "VALIDATE PASSWORD", I usually say Y and pick 2 (Strong). Follow the prompts to remove anonymous users and the test database.

Step 3: Install PHP 8.3
Ubuntu 24.04 ships with PHP 8.3. We need php-fpm (to talk to Nginx) and php-mysql (to talk to your database).
sudo apt install php-fpm php-mysql -y

Step 4: Configure Nginx for your Domain
We need to tell Nginx to use PHP and where your files are.
1. Create the directory:
sudo mkdir -p /var/www/twendeee.site
sudo chown -R $USER:$USER /var/www/twendeee.site
2. Create the config:
sudo nano /etc/nginx/sites-available/twendeee.site
3. Paste this exact block:
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name twendeee.site www.twendeee.site;
    root /var/www/twendeee.site;
    index index.php index.html index.htm;

    location / {
        try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
    }

    location ~ \.php$ {
        include snippets/fastcgi-php.conf;
        fastcgi_pass unix:/run/php/php8.3-fpm.sock;
    }
}

4. Enable and Test:
sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/twendeee.site /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/
sudo nginx -t
sudo systemctl restart nginx

Step 5: Get your SSL Certificate (The final touch)
sudo apt install certbot python3-certbot-nginx -y
sudo certbot --nginx -d twendeee.site -d www.twendeee.site

1. Create a Test File
nano /var/www/twendeee.site/index.html
Paste this in:
<h1>Hello! Your website is now live!</h1>
(Save with Ctrl+O, Enter, then Ctrl+X to exit).

2. Fix Permissions
# Set the owner to www-data (the web server user)
sudo chown -R www-data:www-data /var/www/twendeee.site
sudo chmod -R 755 /var/www/twendeee.site

3. Verify Nginx can "See" the Path
sudo chmod +x /var/www

4. Restart Nginx
sudo nginx -t
sudo systemctl restart nginx

How to Secure Your Server with UFW
1. Allow SSH (Termius):
sudo ufw allow OpenSSH
2. Enable the Firewall:
sudo ufw enable
(Press y when it warns you about disrupting connections).
Now check the status again:
sudo ufw status or sudo ufw status verbose


Here is the exact step-by-step for chocohills.com.

Step 1: Namecheap DNS (The "Two A Records" Way)
Go to the Advanced DNS tab for chocohills.com and add these two records:

A Record

Host: @

Value: 160.x.x.x

A Record

Host: www

Value: 160.x.x.x

Step 2: Create the Folders
sudo mkdir -p /var/www/chocohills.com
sudo chown -R $USER:$USER /var/www/chocohills.com

Step 3: Create the Nginx Config
sudo nano /etc/nginx/sites-available/chocohills.com
Paste this in:
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name chocohills.com www.chocohills.com;
    root /var/www/chocohills.com;
    index index.php index.html index.htm;

    location / {
        try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
    }

    location ~ \.php$ {
        include snippets/fastcgi-php.conf;
        fastcgi_pass unix:/run/php/php8.3-fpm.sock;
    }
}
(Save with Ctrl+O, Enter, then Ctrl+X).

Step 4: Activate the New Site
Link the file and restart Nginx:
sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/chocohills.com /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/
sudo nginx -t
sudo systemctl restart nginx

Step 5: Install the SSL Certificate
Wait about 2 minutes for the DNS to settle, then run Certbot:
sudo certbot --nginx -d chocohills.com -d www.chocohills.com

Step 6: Fix Permissions
Because you'll be uploading files via SFTP later, make sure Nginx has the right permissions for this new folder:
sudo chown -R www-data:www-data /var/www/chocohills.com
sudo chmod -R 755 /var/www/chocohills.com















